was thinking a little more about this. So if we create the PollerFlux like below then parameter validations are delayed until consumer subscribe.
new PollerFlux<Foo, Void>(Duration.ofMillis(3),
    // The Activation Function
    new Function<PollingContext<Foo>, Mono<Foo>>() {
        @Override
        public Mono<Foo> apply(PollingContext<Foo> pollingContext) {
            Mono<Foo> initMono = startLro(start_params);
            return initMono;
        }
    },
    // The Poll Function
    new Function<PollingContext<Foo>, Mono<PollResponse<Foo>>>() {
        @Override
        public Mono<PollResponse<Foo>> apply(PollingContext<Foo> fooPollingContext) {
            Mono<PollResponse<Foo>> pollMono = doOnePoll(poll_params);
            return pollMono;
        }
    },
    // The Cancel Function
    ....,
    // The final result function
    ....);

Any such delayed param validation error from the activation function will be bubbled up.
But any such delayed param validation error from poll function will not bubbled up since the polling loop continue to poll on error.

The above behavior of two functions are the same for both local param validation and the server returned an error. The PollerFlux.error cannot be used in this pattern.
On the other hand, if we create the PollerFlux like below where we do param validation eagerly in sync path then yes we can use PollerFlux.error to catch and convert to async error.
But PollerFlux.error is not to bubble up the error that poller function produce in the async path (e.g. error from service), polling loop will continue to poll like today.  I guess we are aware of this but wanted to ensure.
new PollerFlux<Foo, Void>(Duration.ofMillis(3),
    // The Activation Function
    getStartMonoFunction(start_params),
    // The Poll Function
    getPollMonoFunction(poll_params),
    // The Cancel Function
    ...,
    // The final result function
    ...);

// The Activation Function
Function<PollingContext<Foo>, Mono<Foo>> getStartMonoFunction(start_params) {
    // validation of "start_params" parameters and throwing of error outside reactor path
    return new Function<PollingContext<Foo>, Mono<Foo>>() {
        @Override
        public Mono<Foo> apply(PollingContext<Foo> pollingContext) {
            Mono<Foo> initMono = startLro(start_params);
            return initMono;
        }
    };
}

// The Poll Function
Function<PollingContext<Foo>, Mono<PollResponse<Foo>>> getPollMonoFunction(poll_params) {
     // validation of "poll_params" and throwing of error outside reactor path
    return new Function<PollingContext<Foo>, Mono<PollResponse<Foo>>>() {
        @Override
        public Mono<PollResponse<Foo>> apply(PollingContext<Foo> fooPollingContext) {
            Mono<PollResponse<Foo>> pollMono = doOnePoll(poll_params);
            return pollMono;
        }
    };
}

Yes, @anuchandy, you are right. The intention of creating this method is to do input validation in our public APIs. For e.g.
public PollerFlux<Foo, Bar> beginPollingOperation(String data, Duration interval) {
    try {
        // All these input validations need to be done right here but will be surfaced to the user through proper error channel by returning PollerFlux.error()
         Objects.requireNonNull(data);
         Objects.requireNonNull(interval);
         if(interval.isZero()) {
               throw IllegalArgumentException("'interval' cannot be zero");
         }
         return new PollerFlux(.....);
    }
    catch (Exception ex) {
          return PollerFlux.error(ex);
    }
}

